So lets recap:‚ñ∂Ô∏èMust be QSB‚ñ∂Ô∏èQSB issues new stock‚ñ∂Ô∏èHold for five or more years‚ñ∂Ô∏èExclude $10M in gain (or more) on sale‚ñ∂Ô∏èStack ownership to multiple the effect‚ñ∂Ô∏èBut be careful that you don't bust your status! (/end)

‚ñ∂Ô∏è Many in Congress view QSBS as a "loophole" that they are clamoring to eliminate‚ñ∂Ô∏è You only get the exclusion if you sell stock, not assets‚ñ∂Ô∏è There are a number of rules that have to be followed that can bust QSBS eligibility and result in cap gains taxes and penalties (25/x)

Now, I'll wrap this up with a couple caveats, because it's not all sunshine and lollipops in QSBS-land.So what do you need to know?‚ñ∂Ô∏è A QSB is a C Corp, so it's paying corporate income tax every year while you wait for your exit  (24/x)

üö®üö® Note that there is some dispute in the way Section 1202 is written that both spouses get their own exemption.If you want to be safe, you can use non-grantor trusts to get the same effect with greater certainty that it won't be challenged by the IRS. (23/x)

So now, just by being thoughtful about making your investment 50/50 your spouse:‚ñ∂Ô∏è Each of you has $9.5M gain‚ñ∂Ô∏è Each of you can exclude the entire $9.5M gain‚ñ∂Ô∏è You pay zero capital gains tax on the entire $19M gain!See the power of QSBS with proper planning?! (22/x)

As a reminder, $1M basis in 1M shares, selling for $20M.So each of you have $500k basis in your QSBS and each of you sells all of your QSBS for $10.0M.That's a $9.5M gain for you and your wife.As I mentioned above, the exclusion is PER PERSON! (21/x)

And by creatively structuring your sale, you've increased your exclusion from $10M up to $14.5M!!But lets go one step further and assume you want the complete exit in year 6.Same facts...except your married and your spouse owns 50% of the original QSBS. (20/x)

So let's review what happened:Over 2 years you sold $1M of QSBS for total gain of $21.5M and excluded $14.5M of that gain from cap gains tax.At current cap gains tax rates, you've saved millions of dollars in capital gains taxes! (19/x)

But remember, the annual exclusion doesn't take prior year exclusions into account.So now, you take 10x your basis ($500k basis times 10 = $5M)...and exclude $5M, so you pay cap gains tax on $7.0M ($12.0M gain on sale minus $5M exclusion). (18/x)

Next year, in year 7, the valuation has not gone up to $25M and you now sell your other 500k shares of QSBS.You now have $12.0M in gain ($12.5 sales price minus $500k basis).Under the cumulative exclusion, you already excluded $9.5M so you only have $500k left. (17/x)

Here's where it gets crazy.The $10M cumulative exclusion takes prior year exclusions into account...But that annual 10x basis exclusion does not!So in this case, you take the $9.5M cumulative exclusion and pay zero cap gains because... (16/x)

$9.5M gain ($10M sales price minus $500k basis).You get a $9.5M exclusion of gain (out of your $10M max) and pay zero capital gains.ORYou exclude 10x your basis ($500k times 10 = $5M) against the annual exemption.Which do you choose? (15/x)

Now assume the business isn't sold in year 6, but instead you sell 50% of your stock to a new investor.Same valuation of $20M. 50% of stock means 500,000 shares for $10M.Your basis was $1.00/share, so total basis of QSBS sold is $500k.Now lets re-run the analysis. (14/x)
OR10x basis is excluded ($1M basis times 10 = $10M).10x annual exclusion of $10M, so you owe tax on $9M.WAITThat seems like exactly the same result. What gives?Stay with me here... (13/x)

Now let's assume the business is sold 6 years later for $20M.You get either a cumulative exclusion of $10M of gain, or annual exclusion of 10x your basis.Total gain is $19M ($20M sales price minus $1M basis).$10M cumulative gain is excluded so you owe tax on $9M. (12/x)

Lets pause for a second on what we mentioned earlier about the tax exemption on $10M cumulatively or 10x basis annually.What does this mean?Let's break it down and show the compounding effect of QSBS.Assume 1,000,000 shares of QSBS with a basis of $1.00/share. (11/x)

Ok, sounds amazing right?Who WOULDN'T want to structure their biz for QSBS?Well, QSBS doesn't come without some drawbacks:‚è∫Ô∏èQSB has to be a C Corp‚è∫Ô∏èQSBS exemption is only recognized on a sale of stock, not sale of assets (the favored method of exit for SMBs). (10/x)

That is huge, and can mean literally millions in tax savings.But there's an even more powerful aspect to this:‚ñ∂Ô∏è It's an exclusion per person AND per company!Your kids and spouse get their own exclusion, so with proper estate planning, you can compound the effect! (9/x)

Now that you hold QSBS, what does that mean for you?üö®If you hold the QSBS for 5 years or more, you can exclude up to the greater of $10M (cumulatively) or 10x your basis in the QSBS (per year) from capital gains tax on the sale of the QSBS! (8/x)

So I say "nothing", but I really mean you need to document the stock purchase properly!It's not uncommon to include language in a stock purchase agreement when making an investment that explicitly recites the parties' intent to treat the stock as QSBS. (7/x)

Alright, so I just bought stock in a QSB. What do I need to do to make it QSBS?Well...nothing, really.There's no filing to be made. Either the stock qualifies or it doesn't, and if it's challenged in an audit, you have to show how it qualifies as QSBS. (6/x)

In other words, you can't "inherit" QSBS by buying stock from another person.Only new shares issued directly by the qualified small business to an investor in exchange for money or services can qualify.This is an important distinction for buyers. More on this below! (5/x)

So we have a QSB...how do we get QSBS?Simple...a QSB issues NEW stock to a shareholder in exchange for money or services.That's it.But why did I put "NEW" in all caps?Because only newly issued stock qualifies! (4/x)

What businesses are prohibited from qualifying?‚ñ∂Ô∏è Personal/Prof services‚ñ∂Ô∏è Banking/insurance/finance‚ñ∂Ô∏è Farming & mining‚ñ∂Ô∏è Hotels & RestaurantsEverything else is fair game (manufacturing, retail, tech, etc). (3/x)

There are a number of important factors:1Ô∏è‚É£ It must be a C Corp for tax purposes2Ô∏è‚É£ It must have < $50M in assets at issuance3Ô∏è‚É£ Must be active business (not holding company...with exceptions)4Ô∏è‚É£ Must not be a prohibited business (2/x)

Let's start at the beginning.QSBS means "Qualified Small Business Stock".It is stock that is issued by a "qualified small business" (QSB).How does a business qualify as a "qualified small business"? (1/x)
